        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The goals of the observation proposed here are simple: map the source of the continuum (sub)millimeter emission at high-resolution in both the 345 GHz continuum and the line 
emission of CO and 13CO to determine (a) whether the emission is from a Keplerian disk and (b) if it has a cavity commensurate with it being a circum-triple Keplerian disk. 

The spectral setup provides 2 spectral windows to provide pseudo-continuum converage at 344.75 and 331.65 GHz.  Dual polarization observations with these two spectral windows 
provide 4 GHz of continuum coverage (per polarization) and will allow sensitive continuum mapping at ~0.2 mJy/beam RMS. Because the "depth" of the gap in the image plane is 
expected to be of order a few mJy (as seen in Figure 1b of the science justification), achieving the quoted RMS will 
allow an extremely secure detection of any gap similar to what we propose must obtain in the GW Ori disk.  The other two spectral windows available are reserved for high spectral 
resolution observations of the gas lines CO(J=3-2) and 13CO(J=3-2) will allow for dynamical mass estimates of the stellar system, as well as an assessment of the disk geometry 
(13CO being necessary in the case that the CO line is optically thick). The high spectral resolution (delta v ~ 28 m/s) is desirable because the probable disk geometry is face-on.

As noted in the science proposal, in addition to the high angular resolution observations necessary to resolve the gap, we also require observations with shorter baselines to ensure that 
we can properly map the system's large-scale structure.  Previous 229 GHz observations (Figure 2 of the science justification) of the system indicate that the 229 GHz continuum visibility 
changes dramatically from 0 to 100 kilolambda. Therefore, a snapshot observation with ALMA's most compact configuration will be necessary to ensure proper imaging of the system.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
