    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Circumbinary disks hold continuing interest in the planet formation community as they are the likely progenitors of circumbinary planets. These systems may form and evolve differently than  planets orbiting isolated stars or single components of multiples. Though in principle rotationally supported structures around more than two stars are possible, none has so-far been observed. In this proposal, we outline the evidence that one young multiple system -- GW Ori -- may, indeed, provide the first example of a massive disk around more than two stars. We propose high angular resolution (0.1 arcsecond) Band 7 observations of the system to confirm this hypothesis.
</prp:abstract>
